            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology">West (Maghreb) &gt; Morocco &gt; Central Group</p>
               <p>bedouin-type dialect</p>
            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p>The <hi rendition="#i">Zʕīr</hi> is an Arabic-speaking tribal confederacy of mixed <hi rendition="#i">Maʕqil</hi>-Arab and 
                   Berber origins. <hi rendition="#i">Maʕqil</hi> Arabs are probably of Yemenite origin. Between the 
                   12th and the 13th century they entered Morocco heading south of the High Atlas, 
                   after which they returned towards the north to finally settle south of Rabat.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:F5JBJNYA">Loubignac 1952</rs> is a large and hitherto the only collection of texts in the dialect of 
                   the <hi rendition="#i">Zʕīr</hi>. The collection of the data goes back to 1915. It comprises 22 narratives 
                   and 36 ethnographic texts with French translations. Furthermore, the study includes 
                   58 riddles, linguistic commentary to the presented texts as well 
                   as a comprehensive lexicon.</p>
                <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:FY5XKCZN">Aguadé 1998</rs> offers an overview of the dialect of the <hi rendition="#i">Ūlād Xlīfa</hi>, which belong 
                    to the <hi rendition="#i">Zʕīr</hi>. The grammatical sketch includes information on phonology 
                    as well as verbal and nominal morphology.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="dictionaries">
               <head>Dictionaries</head>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:F5JBJNYA">Loubignac 1952</rs> includes a 240 page lexicon.</p>
            </div>

